🔥 Advanced Go Concurrency Gotchas (Production Level)
These are the ones that break real backend systems.

1️⃣ Goroutine Leak (Silent Killer)
❌ Bad Code
func worker(ch chan int) {
	for {
		v := <-ch
		fmt.Println(v)
	}
}
If:

channel never closed

sender stops

no context cancellation

👉 This goroutine will live forever.

🔥 In production:
Memory slowly increases

CPU stable

Hard to detect

✅ Proper Pattern (With Context)
func worker(ctx context.Context, ch <-chan int) {
	for {
		select {
		case v := <-ch:
			fmt.Println(v)
		case <-ctx.Done():
			return
		}
	}
}
Always use:

context

channel close

graceful shutdown

2️⃣ Unbounded Goroutines (1M RPS Disaster)
❌ Dangerous Pattern
http.HandleFunc("/", func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
	go processRequest(r)
})
If traffic spikes:

50K requests

50K goroutines

memory explosion

✅ Worker Pool Pattern
jobs := make(chan Request, 1000)

for i := 0; i < 100; i++ {
	go worker(jobs)
}

func handler(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
	jobs <- Request{}
}
Bound concurrency.

3️⃣ Channel Blocking Under Load
Unbuffered channel:

ch := make(chan int)
If sender faster than receiver → blocking → throughput collapse.

✅ Solution
Use buffered channel:

ch := make(chan int, 10000)
But:

⚠️ Large buffer = memory spike risk.

Better: Use backpressure logic.

4️⃣ Context Ignored in HTTP / DB / Kafka
Very common production mistake.

❌ Wrong
db.Query("SELECT ...")
No timeout.

If DB hangs → goroutine leak.

✅ Correct
ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), 2*time.Second)
defer cancel()

db.QueryContext(ctx, "SELECT ...")
Always propagate context.

5️⃣ sync.Mutex Lock Contention
Heavy lock use:

mu.Lock()
counter++
mu.Unlock()
Under 1M RPS → CPU spikes.

✅ Use Atomic
var counter int64

atomic.AddInt64(&counter, 1)
Much faster.

6️⃣ RWMutex Misuse
People think RWMutex is always faster.

Not true.

If:

Writes frequent

Reads frequent

RWMutex becomes slower than Mutex.

7️⃣ Closing Channel From Receiver
Only sender should close.

❌

go func() {
	close(ch)
}()
If sender still writing → panic.

8️⃣ Slice Shared Between Goroutines
data := []int{}

go func() {
	data = append(data, 1)
}()

go func() {
	data = append(data, 2)
}()
Race condition.

9️⃣ defer Inside High Throughput Loop
for i := 0; i < 1000000; i++ {
	defer fmt.Println(i)
}
Each defer allocates.

Under heavy load → performance drop.

🔟 Large Struct Passed By Value
func process(req BigRequest) {}
Copies entire struct.

Better:

func process(req *BigRequest) {}
1️⃣1️⃣ select Without Default
select {
case ch <- value:
}
If no receiver → blocks forever.

Add default if non-blocking behavior required.

1️⃣2️⃣ time.After Memory Leak Pattern
for {
	select {
	case <-time.After(1 * time.Second):
		fmt.Println("tick")
	}
}
Each time.After allocates timer.

Better:

ticker := time.NewTicker(time.Second)
defer ticker.Stop()

for {
	select {
	case <-ticker.C:
		fmt.Println("tick")
	}
}
1️⃣3️⃣ JSON Marshalling in Hot Path
json.Marshal(obj)
Allocates heavily.

In 1M RPS system:

GC pressure increases

latency spikes

Use:

sync.Pool

reuse buffers

1️⃣4️⃣ Not Using pprof in Production
Many engineers guess performance issues.

Instead use:

go tool pprof http://localhost:6060/debug/pprof/goroutine
1️⃣5️⃣ Kafka Consumer Goroutine Leak Pattern
Common mistake:

for {
	msg := consumer.ReadMessage(-1)
	go process(msg)
}
If process slower than consumption:

infinite goroutines

OOM

Use:

worker pool

max in-flight limit

🚨 Real Production Failure Scenario
High RPS API:

Each request spawns 3 goroutines

No context timeout

Redis slow

Goroutines pile up

GC spikes

Latency 5ms → 2 seconds

System crashes

Root cause:
Unbounded goroutines + no timeout.

🧠 Golden Rules for High-Performance Go
Never spawn unbounded goroutines

Always pass context

Prefer atomic over mutex (when safe)

Measure with pprof

Use worker pools

Avoid shared mutable memory

Close channels correctly

Design backpressure

